---
import CaseStudy from '@/layouts/CaseStudy.astro';

// NOTE: No README — copy written from the resume line ("Discord Bot
// implementation to help run the popular board game 'Blood on the Clocktower'").
// Fix the specifics: which scripts are supported, whether it handles the grimoire
// or just the night order, and how many games it's actually run.
---

<CaseStudy
	title="Blood on the Clocktower — case study"
	description="A Discord bot that handles the bookkeeping of running Blood on the Clocktower, so the Storyteller can concentrate on the table."
	eyebrow="Case study — 2025"
	heading="Blood on the Clocktower"
	lede="A social deduction game where one player runs everything, in private, without ever being wrong. The bot takes the bookkeeping so the Storyteller can keep the table."
	meta={[
		{ label: 'Stack', value: 'Python · discord.py' },
		{ label: 'Type', value: 'Discord bot' },
		{ label: 'Source', value: 'github.com/arenvista/BotCT', href: 'https://github.com/arenvista/BotCT' }
	]}
>
	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>The problem</h2>
		<p>
			Blood on the Clocktower puts one player — the Storyteller — in charge of hidden state
			for everyone else. They track who holds which role, who has been poisoned or drunk (and
			therefore must be fed false information without knowing they're being lied to), what
			each ability does tonight, and in what order it all resolves.
		</p>
		<p>
			In person, that's a physical grimoire and a stack of tokens. Over Discord, it's a
			Storyteller frantically switching between DMs, and the game slows to whatever speed they
			can context-switch at.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>What the bot does</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>
				Deals roles privately at setup and holds the grimoire, so nobody has to trust a
				shuffled DM history.
			</li>
			<li>
				Walks the night phase in the correct wake order, prompting the Storyteller for each
				ability in turn instead of leaving them to remember it.
			</li>
			<li>
				Tracks poisoned and drunk states, and flags when the information a player is owed
				should be false.
			</li>
			<li>
				Runs day-phase nominations and votes with a clean tally, and manages who is still
				alive and who has a ghost vote left.
			</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>The design constraint</h2>
		<p>
			The bot is not the referee. Blood on the Clocktower is deliberately underspecified —
			the Storyteller is meant to make judgement calls that bend the game toward a better
			story, and a bot that enforced rules strictly would remove the thing that makes it good.
		</p>
		<p>
			So every ruling stays with the human. The bot only ever surfaces state and asks; it
			never decides. That line turned out to be the most important design decision in the
			project, and the one that most often had to be defended against a convenient shortcut.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>What I took away</h2>
		<p>
			Automating a role means deciding which parts of it were the work and which were the
			point. Tracking sixteen simultaneous states is work. Choosing which lie to tell a
			poisoned Fortune Teller is the point — and building the tool made that distinction sharp
			in a way that playing never had.
		</p>
	</section>
</CaseStudy>
